<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Chamaecyparis lawsoniana </i>is a conifer that attains a height of 60 m and an age of > 600 years. Trees begin producing seed between 5 and 20 years. Mature trees mast at about 4-5 year intervals. Wind and water dis-perse the winged seeds. Most germination is best on mineral soil in the following spring, when seedlings vigorously colonize recently disturbed sites. Established seedlings are moderately tolerant of shade. Vegetative regeneration is limited to layering of buried or toppled trees. <i>C. lawsoniana </i>is a shade-tolerant tree, and all ages are extremely susceptible to a fatal root rot caused by <i>Phytophthora lateralis </i>(Uchytil 1990d, Zobel 1990). <br/>
<br/>
Most stands of <i>C. lawsoniana </i>are associated with wet meadow, fen, or riparian sites on ultramafic sub-strates, including gabbro, peridotite, and serpentine. Stands span a wide elevation range and may be associated with low-elevation stands of the <i>Pseudotsuga menziesii </i>alliance up to those of <i>Abies </i>x <i>shastensis </i>or even <i>Tsuga mertensiana </i>at highest elevation, inland occurrences. Only in the westernmost stands at low elevations does <i>C. lawsoniana </i>occupy nonserpentine sedimentary substrates (Alexander et al. 2007, Sawyer 2007). <br/>
<br/>
Bingham (1999) developed a region-wide alliance-level classification for late-seral-stage forests based on relationships between species composition and major environmental gradients. Stands dominated by <i>C. lawsoniana </i>segregated signif icantly from the other alliances. This alliance is mainly at middle to high elevations. Stands with <i>Notholithocarpus densiflorus </i>in the tree canopy are included in the <i>Pseudotsuga menziesii- Notholithocarpus densiflorus </i>alliance at lower elevations (Sawyer 2006, 2007). </div>
</div>

    
	
	
