    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Klamath Mountains</b> (M261Aa-d, Aj-k, An). <i>Chamaecyparis lawsoniana</i> grows in two isolated parts of the section. A western population encompasses the Smith, nearby Klamath, and lower Trinity river watersheds centering on the Siskiyou Mountains. The eastern population centers on the headwaters of the Sacramento and Trinity rivers in the Trinity Mountains (Griffin and Critchfield 1972). Stands at Adorni, L. E. Horton, Cedar Basin, and Upper Goose Creek rRNAs (Cheng 2004), in the Siskiyou Mountains (Sawyer and Thornburgh 1969, Simpson 1980), and generally in the Six Rivers National Forest (Jimerson 1994, Jimerson et al. 1995, Sawyer 2007) offer descriptions of the alliance.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast</b> (263Ab). Individuals of <i>C. lawsoniana</i> exist in Del Norte and Humboldt Cos. These are categorized mostly as components of <i>Sequoia sempervirens</i> stands, as at Yurok RNA (Taylor 1982, see Cheng 2004).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> The water-borne root rot <i>Phytophthora lateralis </i>has severely affected stands in the Smith River drainage (Zobel 1990) and in the northern parts of its range in southwestern Oregon. Recent infections exist in the Klamath River drainage at Fish Lake and at high elevations in the Sacramento River drainage. A substantial decline in population size is conceivable for this endemic tree because mud on vehicle tires is the main method of dispersal (Jules et al. 2002). A different RNA (Scott Camp Creek) in the upper Sacramento River drainage was recommended recently because this location is expected to be a more protected site from root rot infection than the previously nominated Cedar Basin RNA (H. Safford and J. Nelson pers. comm. 2006). </div>
</div>

    

    

